							<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
								<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
							</svg>
						</summary>
						<p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
							<strong>Mini gastric bypass</strong> uses one intestinal connection compared to two in traditional bypass, making it <strong>technically simpler with shorter surgery time</strong> (90-120 minutes vs 2-3 hours). Weight loss outcomes are similar (65-75% vs 70-80%). Mini bypass has slightly higher bile reflux risk (1-2%) but lower internal hernia risk. Both procedures require lifelong vitamin supplementation and deliver excellent diabetes remission rates.
						</p>
					</details>

					<details class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 group">
						<summary class="font-semibold text-lg text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
							How much weight will I lose with mini gastric bypass?
							<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
								<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
							</svg>
						</summary>
						<p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
							Most mini gastric bypass patients lose <strong>65-75% of their excess body weight</strong> within 12-18 months. For example, someone 60kg overweight may lose 39-45kg. Weight loss is most rapid in the first 6 months. Results are comparable to traditional gastric bypass and superior to gastric sleeve. Individual results vary based on adherence to diet, exercise, and lifestyle changes. Long-term success requires permanent lifestyle modifications and vitamin supplementation.
						</p>
					</details>

					<details class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 group">
						<summary class="font-semibold text-lg text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
							Can mini gastric bypass be reversed?
							<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
								<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
							</svg>
						</summary>
						<p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
							<strong>Yes, mini gastric bypass can be reversed or revised</strong> if necessary, though reversal is uncommon. The single connection point makes reversal technically simpler than traditional gastric bypass. Some patients may require revision to traditional bypass if bile reflux becomes problematic. The procedure can also be converted to other bariatric procedures if needed. However, most patients achieve excellent results without requiring reversal.
						</p>
					</details>

					<details class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 group">
						<summary class="font-semibold text-lg text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
							What is dumping syndrome and will I get it?
							<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
								<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
							</svg>
						</summary>
						<p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
							Dumping syndrome affects <strong>15-20% of mini gastric bypass patients</strong>. It occurs when food moves too quickly from the stomach to the small intestine, causing nausea, cramping, diarrhoea, sweating, and dizziness. It's typically triggered by high-sugar or high-fat foods. Most patients learn to manage it through diet modifications (avoiding sugar, eating slowly, smaller meals). Symptoms often improve over time and can actually help enforce healthy eating habits.
						</p>
					</details>

					<details class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 group">
						<summary class="font-semibold text-lg text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
							Why choose mini gastric bypass over traditional gastric bypass?
							<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
								<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
							</svg>
						</summary>
						<p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">
							Mini gastric bypass offers <strong>similar weight loss and diabetes outcomes with shorter surgery time</strong> and simplified technique. The single connection point reduces surgical complexity and may lead to faster recovery. It has lower internal hernia risk compared to traditional bypass. However, some surgeons prefer traditional bypass due to its longer track record (50+ years vs 30 years). Discuss both options with your surgeon to determine the best choice for your specific situation.
						</p>
